			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/24/opinion/nyto-working/nyto-working-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/24/opinion/nyto-working/nyto-working-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/24/opinion/nyto-working/nyto-working-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003018979" width="592" height="586" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="586"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//op-talk.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/07/24/do-you-work-too-much/" data-title="Do You Work Too Much?" data-description="Researchers and workers themselves are paying increasing attention to the problem of overwork, and some say the culture of certain professions makes burnout inevitable.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The American economy generally operates on the assumption that the more hours you work, the better an employee you are. But increasingly, researchers and workers themselves are saying that working to the point of burnout can be unhealthy, unproductive, and even dangerous â and some are advocating for large-scale solutions that tackle the problem at its source.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At Time, Alexandra Sifferlin <a href="//time.com/3004782/burnout-in-the-hospital-why-doctors-are-set-up-for-stress/">looks at</a>Â burnout among physicians. She writes, â<a href="//jama.jamanetwork.com/article.aspx?articleid=1161849" target="_blank">Research</a>Â shows that up to 40% of U.S. doctors experience emotional, physical, and psychological burnout from their jobs, and the consequences are no different for them than they are for people in other occupations â substance abuse and cutting corners.â And she cites a paper published (appropriately enough) in the new journal Burnout Research, in which the psychology professor Anthony Montgomery <a href="//www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2213058614000084">delves into</a> some possible causes of doctor burnout â and its dangers. He argues that the medical profession may be exceptionally bad at taking care of its own, which hampers doctorsâ ability to care for others:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âHealthcare systems across Europe and the US have systematically highlighted the importance of treating patients as whole people, not just as diseases, but health professionals seem to be exempt from this holistic view, as indicated by the high numbers of burnout. Today there is enough evidence to suggest that expecting health professionals to deliver safe, efficient and patient centred care, while they are getting more and more burnt-out, is not only ineffective but also costly and dangerous as indicated by the increasing numbers of medical mistakes, and patient neglect.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At The Huffington Post, Jennifer Bendery <a href="//www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/07/21/judicial-vacancy-report_n_5607416.html">examines</a> burnout in another high-pressure profession: the federal judiciary. She cites a new <a href="//www.brennancenter.org/sites/default/files/publications/Impact%20of%20Judicial%20Vacancies%20072114.pdf">report</a> by Alicia Bannon at the Brennan Center for Justice Analysis, which finds that vacancies on the federal bench are leaving judges overstretched. âI sense a weariness and a tiredness on behalf of our district judges,â says one judge in the report. Another adds:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âItâs like an emergency room in a hospital. The judges are used to it and people come in and out and get good treatment. But the question is, can you sustain it? Eventually you burn out.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The website Lifehacker has long offered advice on identifying and combatting burnout. In a 2012 post, Adam Dachis <a href="//lifehacker.com/5884439/burnout-is-real-how-to-identify-the-problem-and-how-to-fix-it">defines</a> the ailment:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âBurnout isnât as simple as extreme exhaustion. When youâre truly burnt out, thereâs very little youâll do that isnât necessary for survival. You wonât find a regular vacation very refreshing. You not only lose interest in the work that burnt you out in the first place, but in nearly everything else that you do. Fun wonât be fun, every little thing will bother you, and youâll be unhappy without fully understanding why. Youâll feel this way on a regular basis, and youâll likely believe there isnât an alternative.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">His advice for fixing the problem:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWhatever is at the source, you need to cut it off. If your source of burnout is job-related, figure out what the problem is and do everything you can to change it. If you change isnât an option within your job, it may be time to quit.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If you canât quit, Mr. Dachis recommends seeking help from friends, getting exercise, and changing your daily habits: âReversing your routine is a simple way to feel refreshed and it takes very little work.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Justin Jackson, a product manager and writer, <a href="//justinjackson.ca/the-principle-that-changed-my-life/">outlined</a> his own cure for burnout in a blog post (also <a href="//lifehacker.com/the-80-rule-cutting-back-on-work-makes-you-work-bette-1602976354">cited</a> on Lifehacker):</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI became conscious of the amount of energy I spent at the office.Â I would deliberately pace myself so I that I spent only 80% of my mental energy throughout the day.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThereâs not really a good way of describing how I determine whether or not Iâm at 80%.Â Itâs a state of being mindful.Â I try not to overstimulate my brain: I pick 2-3 big things to accomplish a day. After that, I focus on little things that donât require as much energy.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But Mr. Montgomery argues that for doctors, changes at the individual level arenât enough: âThe failure of occupational health psychology to find a âcureâ for burnout should rid us of the notion that we simply need to train our physicians to be better able to cope with the rigours of their profession.â Instead, he points to a systemic problem: Medical schools emphasize individual performance above all else, but the actual practice of medicine requires a lot of teamwork. The result: âThis disconnect between their training/expectations and the realities of the need to work with co-workers and patients who have different visions of how the organisation (hospital) should operate means that job burnout is inevitable.â Preventing burnout, he argues, will require challenging medicineâs hyper-individualistic culture, among other reforms: âWe may need to reimagine healthcare in a way that views some errors as unavoidable, demystifies the physicians as superheroes, engages real patient participation and steers healthcare professionals away from cultures of self-preservation.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Others, too, have begun to look at burnout as a social ill, not just an individual one. In a Times examination of the problem in 2013, Alina Tugend <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/11/30/your-money/a-solution-to-burnout-that-doesnt-mean-less-work.html?pagewanted=all&amp;module=Search&amp;mabReward=relbias%3Ar%2C%7B%221%22%3A%22RI%3A7%22%7D">wrote</a>:</p>
<p itemprop="articleBody">âMichael Leiter, a professor of occupational health at Acadia University in Nova Scotia, has studied the issue for many years in hospitals. He said burnout was certainly growing among nurses, and younger nurses were experiencing it more than older nurses.</p>
<p itemprop="articleBody">âHe attributed that to the push to work harder with fewer resources, less pay and greater job insecurity. Also, as technology allows the lines between work and home to blur, many feel on-call all the time, with no opportunity for respite.â</p>
<p itemprop="articleBody">And at The New Yorker, James Surowiecki <a href="//www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/01/27/the-cult-of-overwork">notes</a> that while businesses have economic incentives to work their employees too hard (âitâs still cheaper to pay one person to work a hundred hours a week than two people to work fifty hours apieceâ), putting in excessive hours can also become so ingrained in the culture of a company or profession that people do it even when theyâre not forced to: âIn a culture that venerates overwork, people internalize crazy hours as the norm.â But working too much can backfire:</p>
<p itemprop="articleBody">âThe perplexing thing about the cult of overwork is that, as weâve known for a while, long hours diminish both productivity and quality. Among industrial workers, overtime raises the rate of mistakes and safety mishaps; likewise, for knowledge workers fatigue and sleep-deprivation make it hard to perform at a high cognitive level.â</p>
<p itemprop="articleBody">System-wide changes like the ones Mr. Montgomery calls for may seem like a lot to ask for. As Mr. Surowiecki points out, other changes to the medical profession have been met with criticism: âWhen new regulations limited medical residentsâ working hours to eighty a week, many doctors complained of declining standards and mollycoddling, and said that it would have a disastrous effect on training.â However, he says, âresidents in Europe work many fewer hours, without harming the quality of medical care.â And across industries, many are starting to argue that addressing the causes of burnout would be better for everyone than continuing to soldier on as if nothingâs wrong.</p>
	</div>
